WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.480 --> 00:00:02.540
&gt;&gt; Male Presenter: Good afternoon everyone.

00:00:02.540 --> 00:00:03.730
My name is Brian Rose.

00:00:03.730 --> 00:00:05.630
I'm
from the photos team.

00:00:05.630 --> 00:00:11.470
I'm here presenting Thomas Hawk
for part of our photographers at Google series.

00:00:11.470 --> 00:00:13.410
Thomas
Hawk is a prolific photographer.

00:00:13.410 --> 00:00:16.240
He's here from the Bay
Area.

00:00:16.240 --> 00:00:18.750
And one of his life goals is to produce more
than one

00:00:18.750 --> 00:00:20.210
million photographs.

00:00:20.210 --> 00:00:22.550
He's well on his way there.

00:00:22.550 --> 00:00:25.340
If you
are on Google+, you'll probably, or actually

00:00:25.340 --> 00:00:27.289
you've almost
certainly seen his photos.

00:00:27.289 --> 00:00:31.420
Either re-shared by his
friends, shared in your own stream or in our

00:00:31.420 --> 00:00:32.870
"what's hot"
stream.

00:00:32.870 --> 00:00:36.309
At 450,000 followers, he's most certainly
one

00:00:36.309 --> 00:00:38.829
of our top followed photographers but he's
also one

00:00:38.829 --> 00:00:40.989
of our most followed users on Google+.

00:00:40.989 --> 00:00:44.610
Last night, he launched his Photo Talk Plus,
Live streamed

00:00:44.610 --> 00:00:47.879
hangouts which he co-hosts with Lotus Carroll
every Wednesday

00:00:47.879 --> 00:00:50.309
evening and I encourage you to check it out
not just

00:00:50.309 --> 00:00:53.120
because I was on there last night.

00:00:53.120 --> 00:00:56.899
[chuckles] For a quick bit of
admin, there will be plenty of time for Q

00:00:56.899 --> 00:00:59.260
and A but I
encourage you to use the microphones on the

00:00:59.260 --> 00:01:02.190
side for the
benefit of our YouTube and video conference

00:01:02.190 --> 00:01:03.190
audience.

00:01:03.190 --> 00:01:04.980
So
with that, please join me in welcoming Thomas

00:01:04.980 --> 00:01:07.610
Hawk for
the photographers at Google series.

00:01:07.610 --> 00:01:08.710
[Applause]

00:01:08.710 --> 00:01:12.800
&gt;&gt; Thomas: Well, thank you Brian.

00:01:12.800 --> 00:01:15.920
And thanks for everybody for
coming out.

00:01:15.920 --> 00:01:17.450
I'm glad to be here at Google.

00:01:17.450 --> 00:01:20.020
I'm a big
fan of Google's.

00:01:20.020 --> 00:01:25.600
I've enjoyed Google+ and all the
great things you guys are doing with photography.

00:01:25.600 --> 00:01:27.660
I'm
happy to be here today.

00:01:27.660 --> 00:01:32.670
Looking forward to sharing some
photos talking a little bit about just sort

00:01:32.670 --> 00:01:35.820
of my vision
in general with photography and how I approach

00:01:35.820 --> 00:01:40.160
it, how I
look at it, how I do what I kind of do.

00:01:40.160 --> 00:01:44.560
Brian said
yeah -- oh, is that better?

00:01:44.560 --> 00:01:45.560
Okay.

00:01:45.560 --> 00:01:50.290
Yeah, my goal is to
publish a million photographs before I die

00:01:50.290 --> 00:01:52.640
which is a
pretty ambitious goal.

00:01:52.640 --> 00:01:55.520
There have been a lot of prolific
photographers over the years.

00:01:55.520 --> 00:01:59.670
I've kind of tried to find
out photographers that are doing that much

00:01:59.670 --> 00:02:02.830
publishing and
there are not a lot of them out there.

00:02:02.830 --> 00:02:08.030
For me, I'm not
sure exactly where that comes from other than

00:02:08.030 --> 00:02:11.849
I have a
desire to constantly be active with photography

00:02:11.849 --> 00:02:15.579
and see
the world through my camera every single day.

00:02:15.579 --> 00:02:19.690
And by
setting a very arduous schedule like that

00:02:19.690 --> 00:02:23.970
and a very lofty
goal, it really helps me to be focused constantly

00:02:23.970 --> 00:02:25.900
on
photography.

00:02:25.900 --> 00:02:31.260
One thing like I would just say everybody
in this room I also have a day job.

00:02:31.260 --> 00:02:33.310
I'm not a
professional photographer.

00:02:33.310 --> 00:02:37.920
And so, one of the questions
I get a lot is how do you do so many photographs?

00:02:37.920 --> 00:02:40.659
How do
you do so much work and still kind of manage

00:02:40.659 --> 00:02:43.439
your other
stuff in your life?

00:02:43.439 --> 00:02:46.269
And so, I'm going to talk a little
bit about that today and what I do.

00:02:46.269 --> 00:02:49.930
In addition to
full-time job, I've got four young kids.

00:02:49.930 --> 00:02:52.790
I've got a 7,
8, 9, and 11-year-old.

00:02:52.790 --> 00:02:58.130
I've found photography, as
passionate as I am about it, you've really

00:02:58.130 --> 00:03:00.500
got to be
incredibly efficient with it and you've got

00:03:00.500 --> 00:03:02.349
to make it
work for you in every way.

00:03:02.349 --> 00:03:05.060
I'll talk about some of the
things I do to become more efficient in my

00:03:05.060 --> 00:03:10.010
own work as
well as, in addition to that, talk about my

00:03:10.010 --> 00:03:13.420
-- one of my
projects right now which is to photograph

00:03:13.420 --> 00:03:15.159
the 100 largest
American cities.

00:03:15.159 --> 00:03:18.160
I've photographed now 31 of the 100 largest
American

00:03:18.160 --> 00:03:19.160
cities.

00:03:19.160 --> 00:03:20.280
I'm doing more and more each year.

00:03:20.280 --> 00:03:23.450
And so, this
year I'm gonna knock off some more.

00:03:23.450 --> 00:03:28.310
Route 66 from Tulsa through
Los Angeles.

00:03:28.310 --> 00:03:34.109
This year I went to St. Louis and Houston
and Austin and Detroit and a number of other

00:03:34.109 --> 00:03:35.109
places.

00:03:35.109 --> 00:03:36.909
I'll talk
about those trips and how I plan for those

00:03:36.909 --> 00:03:38.569
trips and how
I decide what I'm going to shoot on those

00:03:38.569 --> 00:03:42.400
trips and I how I do those trips as
efficiently as I can.

00:03:42.400 --> 00:03:45.439
I'm also going to talk a little
bit about my experiences photo sharing in

00:03:45.439 --> 00:03:46.700
general.

00:03:46.700 --> 00:03:50.400
I've
been online sharing photos for a while now.

00:03:50.400 --> 00:03:52.920
I guess I
first started in 2003.

00:03:52.920 --> 00:03:57.489
I got involved with Flickr very,
very early and became one of the most active

00:03:57.489 --> 00:04:00.739
Flickr
users and one of the most followed users there.

00:04:00.739 --> 00:04:04.489
And talk about my strategy with that.

00:04:04.489 --> 00:04:07.819
I will say
to start, again like I said before, I'm not

00:04:07.819 --> 00:04:10.120
a
professional photographer although I do make

00:04:10.120 --> 00:04:12.200
money with
my photography.

00:04:12.200 --> 00:04:15.400
It's not my primary source of income.

00:04:15.400 --> 00:04:19.360
I
think that for me being able to focus just

00:04:19.360 --> 00:04:23.280
on my art as a
nonprofessional photographer affords me certain

00:04:23.280 --> 00:04:24.310
luxuries.

00:04:24.310 --> 00:04:28.840
And one of those is I don't care a lot about,
you know,

00:04:28.840 --> 00:04:29.860
making money with my work.

00:04:29.860 --> 00:04:32.640
I don't care if people steal
my work.

00:04:32.640 --> 00:04:34.730
You know, everything is licensed creative
commons.

00:04:34.730 --> 00:04:36.390
I don't watermark things.

00:04:36.390 --> 00:04:40.230
I don't try to
prevent people from getting my stuff.

00:04:40.230 --> 00:04:43.090
My goal as an
artist is that people will see my stuff as

00:04:43.090 --> 00:04:45.760
much as
possible everywhere.

00:04:45.760 --> 00:04:51.630
So because I don't have to worry
about making a living for it, you know, I

00:04:51.630 --> 00:04:53.170
think
that's an important distinction.

00:04:53.170 --> 00:04:55.970
Also I can shoot what I
want to shoot and I can really focus on what

00:04:55.970 --> 00:04:56.970
I really want to
shoot.

00:04:56.970 --> 00:04:59.690
I think for all of you who have day jobs,
that's

00:04:59.690 --> 00:05:01.760
a nice luxury to be able to have a lot of
photographers.

00:05:01.760 --> 00:05:03.920
A lot of professional photographers they don't
have that luxury.

00:05:03.920 --> 00:05:06.840
They have to say, "Well, OK, I'm shooting
these weddings."

00:05:06.840 --> 00:05:08.580
Last
night on our show we interviewed Scott Jarvie

00:05:08.580 --> 00:05:10.100
who's a
professional wedding photographer.

00:05:10.100 --> 00:05:12.440
He's gotta do his weddings and he's gotta
do this.

00:05:12.440 --> 00:05:15.980
He does other stuff
but I think I've got a luxury to be able to

00:05:15.980 --> 00:05:19.480
shoot sort of
whatever I want, which is nice.

00:05:19.480 --> 00:05:23.640
So I'm going to also go
through some pictures up here while we talk,

00:05:23.640 --> 00:05:25.730
in general.

00:05:25.730 --> 00:05:27.280
And sort of talk about that.

00:05:27.280 --> 00:05:30.660
We recently did a trip to
Death Valley.

00:05:30.660 --> 00:05:31.660
Had a great time.

00:05:31.660 --> 00:05:33.910
There are a number of
Googlers on there including our own Brian

00:05:33.910 --> 00:05:43.190
Rose, his wife Kim, out on the
playa . There's some more pictures.

00:05:43.190 --> 00:05:45.160
That's Lotus
Carroll, my co-host.

00:05:45.160 --> 00:05:49.660
Some of you may know Vincent doing a big jump
out on the playa.

00:05:49.660 --> 00:05:55.570
This was a playa called the Racetrack.

00:05:55.570 --> 00:05:57.540
And beautiful colors in Death Valley.

00:05:57.540 --> 00:06:03.550
So I'm going to go through some pictures,
as well.

00:06:03.550 --> 00:06:05.760
You
know, the first thing as far as time goes,

00:06:05.760 --> 00:06:08.360
you know the
question I get a lot is how do you do your

00:06:08.360 --> 00:06:09.360
job?

00:06:09.360 --> 00:06:10.360
How do
you do your kids and how do you still have

00:06:10.360 --> 00:06:11.550
so much time
to take photos?

00:06:11.550 --> 00:06:15.700
The first thing is, the camera goes with
me everywhere.

00:06:15.700 --> 00:06:20.720
If you're serious about photography and
you want to take it up on the side in addition

00:06:20.720 --> 00:06:23.780
to your
job, I would say, being able to carry that

00:06:23.780 --> 00:06:27.540
camera with you everywhere
is a good place to start.

00:06:27.540 --> 00:06:31.050
I take this backpack with me a
lot of places which has all of my lenses as

00:06:31.050 --> 00:06:33.420
well so I'm a
little hard core with it.

00:06:33.420 --> 00:06:39.510
But even if it's just a
Micro Four Thirds or smaller camera or just

00:06:39.510 --> 00:06:42.070
a digital SLR and a
zoom lens, something like that.

00:06:42.070 --> 00:06:43.850
I think carrying it everywhere
you go.

00:06:43.850 --> 00:06:45.470
I find I'll steal time.

00:06:45.470 --> 00:06:48.510
I live in the East Bay
and I work in San Francisco.

00:06:48.510 --> 00:06:51.390
So if I'm going to take the
BART home, I'll purposely backtrack on the

00:06:51.390 --> 00:06:53.490
BART so I can
get a seat so I can be processing photos the

00:06:53.490 --> 00:06:54.690
entire time.

00:06:54.690 --> 00:06:59.210
I
try to make the most efficient use for photography

00:06:59.210 --> 00:07:01.410
of all
of my time that I'm not working or with my

00:07:01.410 --> 00:07:03.670
family or
kids.

00:07:03.670 --> 00:07:05.530
So a big part of that is thinking about that
as

00:07:05.530 --> 00:07:06.530
your day.

00:07:06.530 --> 00:07:07.530
If I'm going to have some exercise.

00:07:07.530 --> 00:07:09.630
Yesterday
I was going to take a walk.

00:07:09.630 --> 00:07:12.660
So you know walk around with
the camera in San Francisco.

00:07:12.660 --> 00:07:16.100
Take it out do an impromptu
photo walk all by yourself.

00:07:16.100 --> 00:07:19.410
I find if you incorporate
other areas of your life like commuting.

00:07:19.410 --> 00:07:22.210
Sometimes when
you're driving you can't process when you're

00:07:22.210 --> 00:07:24.280
driving.

00:07:24.280 --> 00:07:28.450
If
you're commuting; if you're exercising, anything

00:07:28.450 --> 00:07:31.620
you do
find time to do that.

00:07:31.620 --> 00:07:38.650
As far as my project for the 100
largest American cities, I think we all travel.

00:07:38.650 --> 00:07:41.700
And
when I took on this project, I knew that I

00:07:41.700 --> 00:07:44.920
wasn't going
to have a lot of time in individual cities.

00:07:44.920 --> 00:07:46.890
So I wanted
to figure out how I could most efficiently

00:07:46.890 --> 00:07:49.030
shoot those
cities.

00:07:49.030 --> 00:07:51.060
And the first thing I do before I go on a
trip

00:07:51.060 --> 00:07:54.430
is I very carefully research exactly what
I'm going to

00:07:54.430 --> 00:07:55.610
shoot.

00:07:55.610 --> 00:07:57.450
I found Flickr is the best resource for that.

00:07:57.450 --> 00:07:58.680
I'll usually get to a city.

00:07:58.680 --> 00:08:02.350
I'll look for the city of
Chicago or the city of St. Louis.

00:08:02.350 --> 00:08:05.550
I'll sort that by
interestingness on Flickr and I'll look at

00:08:05.550 --> 00:08:09.780
a lot of what
other people have taken, interesting shots.

00:08:09.780 --> 00:08:11.780
I'll get a
lot of my locations from that.

00:08:11.780 --> 00:08:13.140
I'll use that as a
location scout.

00:08:13.140 --> 00:08:15.450
A lot of the photos on Flickr are
geo-tagged.

00:08:15.450 --> 00:08:17.230
If they're not geo-tagged, a lot of times
you can figure out

00:08:17.230 --> 00:08:20.240
where they are anyways.

00:08:20.240 --> 00:08:24.140
And with those points ahead of
my trip I'll make a Google map and I'll go

00:08:24.140 --> 00:08:26.450
in and I'll
make the pinpoints of every place I'm going

00:08:26.450 --> 00:08:29.020
to shoot in
that city and I don't always get to all of

00:08:29.020 --> 00:08:31.350
them on that
map before I ever even leave.

00:08:31.350 --> 00:08:33.610
In fact weeks before.

00:08:33.610 --> 00:08:35.469
And
I'll also coordinate them.

00:08:35.469 --> 00:08:38.060
So if there's something I
really, really want to shoot I'll use a different

00:08:38.060 --> 00:08:39.199
kind of
pin.

00:08:39.199 --> 00:08:43.500
If it's, "well, I'd like to get that; that'd
be nice", I might use a different pin.

00:08:43.500 --> 00:08:46.700
So
before I ever leave, I got a very, very well

00:08:46.700 --> 00:08:51.560
thought out
map of exactly what I'm going to shoot.

00:08:51.560 --> 00:08:58.250
Once I go on the
trip, I'll coordinate my route so I hit a

00:08:58.250 --> 00:08:59.670
lot of the
things in a row.

00:08:59.670 --> 00:09:01.620
I don't want to waste any time.

00:09:01.620 --> 00:09:03.329
I
sleep very little on the trip.

00:09:03.329 --> 00:09:06.620
I usually do long
weekends so I'll do a Friday to Monday because

00:09:06.620 --> 00:09:09.550
I can get
away from work during that time.

00:09:09.550 --> 00:09:14.740
And I'll use every waking hour I can
possible focused on shooting this agenda that

00:09:14.740 --> 00:09:17.430
I've mapped
out for myself.

00:09:17.430 --> 00:09:21.129
I try to avoid driving during rush hour.

00:09:21.129 --> 00:09:23.420
So if I know I'm going to be in a car, I'll
purposely

00:09:23.420 --> 00:09:24.970
plan my trip around that.

00:09:24.970 --> 00:09:28.790
I'll have places that I'm going to be walking
around shooting during rush hour.

00:09:28.790 --> 00:09:31.660
I'll make the most of
my sunrises and sunsets.

00:09:31.660 --> 00:09:35.209
If I'm going to go to Austin,
I want to shoot the Pennybacker Bridge at

00:09:35.209 --> 00:09:36.209
sunrise.

00:09:36.209 --> 00:09:38.370
I'll
be out there; I'll have that already set out.

00:09:38.370 --> 00:09:41.199
So I have my sunsets and sunrises especially
planned.

00:09:41.199 --> 00:09:45.750
Those are always oftentimes times around rush
hour traffic so you want to find a good, very

00:09:45.750 --> 00:09:49.240
picturesque location to
shoot.

00:09:49.240 --> 00:09:51.800
When I am, also when I plan on the trips I
think

00:09:51.800 --> 00:09:53.350
back up is very important.

00:09:53.350 --> 00:09:59.019
I learned early on that inevitably,
for whatever reason, you end up losing photos

00:09:59.019 --> 00:10:00.019
on trips.

00:10:00.019 --> 00:10:01.069
I
don't know what it is.

00:10:01.069 --> 00:10:03.269
It's the one time the hard drive goes bad.

00:10:03.269 --> 00:10:05.180
It's the one time something goes wrong.

00:10:05.180 --> 00:10:07.160
Your memory card malfunctions.

00:10:07.160 --> 00:10:10.029
You accidentally
format your card when you thought you had

00:10:10.029 --> 00:10:13.550
got all your photos
off but you didn't.

00:10:13.550 --> 00:10:15.459
So there's a lot of mistakes you could
make.

00:10:15.459 --> 00:10:22.730
I bring with me just a little one terabyte
FireWire 800 Seagate portable drive, I don't

00:10:22.730 --> 00:10:24.300
remember what they're called, but they're
not that

00:10:24.300 --> 00:10:27.430
expensive and I use that as a Time Machine
drive on my

00:10:27.430 --> 00:10:28.430
Mac.

00:10:28.430 --> 00:10:32.220
So everything gets backed up as I go.

00:10:32.220 --> 00:10:34.910
So if I lose
stuff I'll be able to get it back.

00:10:34.910 --> 00:10:36.990
I have lost stuff; I've
got it back.

00:10:36.990 --> 00:10:38.149
Even recently in Death Valley.

00:10:38.149 --> 00:10:42.180
I went to bed and
I thought all the photos had been copied.

00:10:42.180 --> 00:10:44.269
I thought they
were and I took the card off in the morning

00:10:44.269 --> 00:10:46.480
and I
reformatted and I used it and I realized I

00:10:46.480 --> 00:10:50.060
missed 200 photos
at the end of my Racetrack.

00:10:50.060 --> 00:10:52.029
So I had to use card recovery
software to get them back.

00:10:52.029 --> 00:10:55.279
So I was able to get them
back so you can even when you format a card

00:10:55.279 --> 00:10:58.980
you can still
almost every time get the pictures back with

00:10:58.980 --> 00:10:59.980
recovery
software.

00:10:59.980 --> 00:11:02.649
But you have to be very mindful of losing
pictures.

00:11:02.649 --> 00:11:06.939
Particularly if you're going to go on a trip
you're going to take 10, 12, 13, 15 thousand

00:11:06.939 --> 00:11:07.939
photographs.

00:11:07.939 --> 00:11:08.939
You
want to make sure that they're backed up so

00:11:08.939 --> 00:11:11.610
I clear out a
lot of space on my hard drive on my Mac.

00:11:11.610 --> 00:11:15.470
I got a 750 gigabyte hard drive internally
lot so I make sure I have a lot of room

00:11:15.470 --> 00:11:16.470
there.

00:11:16.470 --> 00:11:19.350
I have a Time Machine drive that backs up
everything.

00:11:19.350 --> 00:11:22.009
I've got a formula where every night when
I

00:11:22.009 --> 00:11:24.760
come in at the end of every night I have to
religiously

00:11:24.760 --> 00:11:25.930
do certain things.

00:11:25.930 --> 00:11:28.579
One is I have to make sure all my cards
are off loaded.

00:11:28.579 --> 00:11:32.380
I don't use Adobe Lightroom to off load
my cards and import it, although I might do

00:11:32.380 --> 00:11:33.380
that at home.

00:11:33.380 --> 00:11:34.380
Because it's slower.

00:11:34.380 --> 00:11:35.620
I just drag and drop them.

00:11:35.620 --> 00:11:37.930
From
this is a date folder to a date folder as

00:11:37.930 --> 00:11:38.930
fast as I can.

00:11:38.930 --> 00:11:41.319
I got a 64 gigabyte card; I've got to get
a lot of pictures off.

00:11:41.319 --> 00:11:44.050
I won't have time; I want to go to sleep.

00:11:44.050 --> 00:11:46.209
I also steal time during the day.

00:11:46.209 --> 00:11:47.209
You do get tired.

00:11:47.209 --> 00:11:48.920
You can't go 20 hours straight.

00:11:48.920 --> 00:11:50.379
So you
need bathroom breaks.

00:11:50.379 --> 00:11:51.930
You need water breaks.

00:11:51.930 --> 00:11:54.680
Starbucks,
I use a lot of times for that.

00:11:54.680 --> 00:11:56.170
Starbucks is great
because they're consistent.

00:11:56.170 --> 00:11:57.529
You know they're going to
have a bathroom.

00:11:57.529 --> 00:12:00.029
[laughter] You know they're going to have
coffee and caffeine

